To fix the SQL Injection vulnerability in the provided Java code snippet, you should use Prepared Statements instead of concatenating user input directly into the SQL query. Prepared Statements help prevent SQL Injection by separating SQL code from user input.

Here is the updated secure version of the code using Prepared Statements:

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class SQLInjectionSecure {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            String username = args[0]; // User input

            String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydatabase";
            String user = "root";
            String password = "password";

            Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, password);

            // Use PreparedStatement to prepare the query
            String query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE username=?";
            PreparedStatement pstmt = con.prepareStatement(query);

            // Set the parameterized value for the username
            pstmt.setString(1, username);

            ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery();

            while (rs.next()) {
                System.out.println("User ID: " + rs.getInt("id") + ", Username: " + rs.getString("username"));
            }

            con.close();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
``

